WEBVTT

1
00:00:01.080 --> 00:00:04.140
Okay. Thank you everyone, and welcome to this

2
00:00:04.960 --> 00:00:08.880
both technology and biology-focused session on spatial

3
00:00:08.940 --> 00:00:11.760
and single-cell genomics at scale.

4
00:00:11.800 --> 00:00:15.620
And it's really a session focused on, I think you'll see, decoding the

5
00:00:15.660 --> 00:00:17.500
ecosystem of tumors.

6
00:00:18.320 --> 00:00:22.200
And I think many of you guys will appreciate that there's been a wealth of

7
00:00:22.240 --> 00:00:23.560
new technologies

8
00:00:24.700 --> 00:00:28.500
that have really recently come to bear on the ability to

9
00:00:28.580 --> 00:00:30.900
measure transcripts at scale within tissues.

10
00:00:31.540 --> 00:00:34.720
I'm a big science fiction fan, and Arthur C.

11
00:00:34.880 --> 00:00:38.860
Clarke has these three laws, and one of them is, "To discover the limits

12
00:00:38.900 --> 00:00:42.490
of what's possible, you have to venture into the impossible." And

13
00:00:42.960 --> 00:00:46.580
you might be able to tell that many of these technologies that we have, being able

14
00:00:46.600 --> 00:00:50.120
to measure the whole transcriptome within cells and tissues would have been maybe

15
00:00:50.160 --> 00:00:53.200
impossible to consider just maybe a decade ago.

16
00:00:53.210 --> 00:00:55.520
And so it's my pleasure to

17
00:00:56.700 --> 00:00:57.769
chair this session and

18
00:00:58.980 --> 00:01:02.720
introduce myself. I'm from the Broad, Dana

19
00:01:03.060 --> 00:01:07.010
from Sloan Kettering, and then Itay from Weizmann, who will talk about three

20
00:01:07.060 --> 00:01:10.920
different aspects of this. And actually, unfortunately, due to some of

21
00:01:10.960 --> 00:01:14.890
the geopolitical circumstances, Itay couldn't make it out here, but he pre-recorded

22
00:01:14.920 --> 00:01:18.380
his talk. All right. So we'll just dive right in.

23
00:01:19.240 --> 00:01:20.720
If I can move...

24
00:01:28.580 --> 00:01:29.520
Okay, great.

25
00:01:30.700 --> 00:01:31.140
Yeah. So,

26
00:01:32.820 --> 00:01:36.380
my lab has really been focused on developing tools and technologies and thinking

27
00:01:36.420 --> 00:01:40.399
about what questions we can answer with these technologies, especially

28
00:01:40.460 --> 00:01:43.880
with respect to measuring the transcriptome within tumor

29
00:01:43.960 --> 00:01:47.820
ecosystems. And one, we've both been interested in the

30
00:01:47.860 --> 00:01:49.980
spatial context and the temporal context.

31
00:01:50.660 --> 00:01:54.570
And this is going to be clear to many of us, but cells really only

32
00:01:54.580 --> 00:01:58.360
make sense in context. For example, this is a zoomed-in H&amp;E image of one cell,

33
00:01:58.780 --> 00:02:01.120
and you might be able to see some features.

34
00:02:01.260 --> 00:02:03.320
It has this funny-looking nuclei.

35
00:02:04.060 --> 00:02:04.620
But really,

36
00:02:05.820 --> 00:02:09.081
it isn't until you see it in the context of the tissue, for example, this is the

37
00:02:09.120 --> 00:02:10.140
Hodgkin lymphoma's

38
00:02:11.060 --> 00:02:14.300
tissue H&amp;E specimen, you might appreciate that it's this large,

39
00:02:14.400 --> 00:02:17.660
multi-nucleated cell surrounded by many other cells of the

40
00:02:17.700 --> 00:02:21.620
microenvironment. And what we've been doing in genomics for a long time

41
00:02:21.660 --> 00:02:25.160
is a little bit like zooming in to that cell and looking at each cell in its

42
00:02:25.220 --> 00:02:29.200
individual context. And it's been focused on dissociated cells.

43
00:02:29.240 --> 00:02:32.890
And it's only been recently that we've been able to bring the full power of

44
00:02:32.920 --> 00:02:36.320
molecular measurements directly within the context of tissues.

45
00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:39.580
The other thing I would just say is that

46
00:02:39.600 --> 00:02:42.720
these measurements are snapshots.

47
00:02:42.760 --> 00:02:46.720
You have to kill the sample, or maybe the sample's already dead, when you

48
00:02:46.760 --> 00:02:50.060
make the measurement, and they're destructive snapshots.

49
00:02:50.080 --> 00:02:53.700
But in fact, to really understand maybe mechanisms, you

50
00:02:53.740 --> 00:02:57.670
might need to understand the progression and the cellular history to understand how

51
00:02:57.680 --> 00:03:01.400
we arrived at the present state. For example, this Hodgkin's lymphoma sample might

52
00:03:01.420 --> 00:03:05.240
have been a healthy lymph node in the past, but there are some evolution of

53
00:03:05.300 --> 00:03:07.840
lineage and exposure that arose this.

54
00:03:07.890 --> 00:03:11.640
And we really have also been quite interested in developing tools to measure

55
00:03:12.060 --> 00:03:15.049
this cellular history directly in the context of tissue.

56
00:03:15.440 --> 00:03:17.640
So I'll touch on both of these in my talk.

57
00:03:18.520 --> 00:03:18.880
And

58
00:03:19.760 --> 00:03:22.960
we've been building a variety of technologies for bringing genomics to tissues,

59
00:03:23.080 --> 00:03:26.680
including ways to measure transcriptomes, genomes, and analysis

60
00:03:26.760 --> 00:03:29.980
tools. I won't talk about this. I just want to say

61
00:03:30.880 --> 00:03:34.700
one thing. A class of these technologies have been built on these

62
00:03:34.720 --> 00:03:37.480
bar-coded arrays. You can see that here.

63
00:03:37.940 --> 00:03:41.440
And this is pretty old now. This is something we

64
00:03:41.460 --> 00:03:43.660
developed six or seven years ago,

65
00:03:45.440 --> 00:03:49.290
actually eight years ago, where we put tissues onto these

66
00:03:49.340 --> 00:03:52.960
arrays that have bar-coded beads, and the beads have XY

67
00:03:53.300 --> 00:03:57.000
locations that are encoded by DNA barcodes, and RNA or

68
00:03:57.040 --> 00:03:58.940
DNA can be captured onto these beads.

69
00:03:59.240 --> 00:04:01.280
And then you know where

70
00:04:02.300 --> 00:04:05.220
those RNA and DNA came from by the DNA barcodes.

71
00:04:05.250 --> 00:04:08.400
And this, obviously, many of you guys have used technologies.

72
00:04:08.880 --> 00:04:11.260
Takara has commercialized this under

73
00:04:13.400 --> 00:04:16.959
this seeker technology we call the Slide-Seq, and then

74
00:04:17.140 --> 00:04:18.529
Visium HD is very similar.

75
00:04:19.570 --> 00:04:23.409
But most recently, a couple of years ago, I feel like we've developed a

76
00:04:23.420 --> 00:04:27.260
version of this technology that we use regularly, and I want to just briefly touch

77
00:04:27.270 --> 00:04:31.000
upon it today, called Slide Tags. And we think it has many

78
00:04:31.020 --> 00:04:34.380
advantages. In fact, we think of it as a kind of a universal

79
00:04:34.440 --> 00:04:38.200
platform to move any single-cell measurement, whether that

80
00:04:38.280 --> 00:04:42.000
is DNA, RNA, epigenomes, directly into the

81
00:04:42.020 --> 00:04:44.900
spatial context. And so how does Slide Tags work?

82
00:04:45.380 --> 00:04:49.280
It works by using these same bar-coded arrays, but instead of

83
00:04:49.300 --> 00:04:52.800
trying to capture the molecules onto the arrays, we invert the

84
00:04:52.820 --> 00:04:56.720
process. Now, we put the tissue onto these arrays, and these

85
00:04:56.760 --> 00:05:00.300
beads have photo-cleavable DNA barcodes.

86
00:05:00.640 --> 00:05:04.070
And then when you cleave these DNA barcodes, they diffuse into the tissue,

87
00:05:04.480 --> 00:05:08.260
allowing these barcodes to be associated with the nuclei.

88
00:05:08.720 --> 00:05:10.160
And this is a little bit like

89
00:05:11.320 --> 00:05:15.120
GPS for cells, because each cell picks up more than one

90
00:05:15.380 --> 00:05:18.140
barcode. It picks up a distribution of barcodes nearby.

91
00:05:18.560 --> 00:05:21.920
And with that, we can localize the cell with very high precision, actually higher

92
00:05:21.960 --> 00:05:24.020
than the 10-micron resolution of the beads.

93
00:05:24.680 --> 00:05:27.180
And it's true single-cell resolution.

94
00:05:27.220 --> 00:05:30.920
We can encode basically the location of each cell that we

95
00:05:30.960 --> 00:05:34.400
sequence with an XY, or the majority of cells we sequence with an XY

96
00:05:34.440 --> 00:05:37.590
location. And it's compatible with any single-cell approach.

97
00:05:37.640 --> 00:05:41.540
And so a lot of the data that I'll show today is with 10X, either Phi Prime

98
00:05:41.600 --> 00:05:42.160
or Flex.

99
00:05:43.040 --> 00:05:46.620
And so here you can see this fancy UMAP,

100
00:05:47.300 --> 00:05:50.840
where each individual cell in this UMAP, this is from mouse

101
00:05:50.880 --> 00:05:53.570
hippocampus, is placed into the context of space.

102
00:05:54.400 --> 00:05:56.360
And what does this really give you?

103
00:05:56.600 --> 00:06:00.400
Well, one thing is it gives you really high-quality, true single-cell

104
00:06:00.460 --> 00:06:03.820
data. You don't have to deal with segmentation or other

105
00:06:04.300 --> 00:06:07.784
sorts of things thatLike result in mixing of

106
00:06:07.824 --> 00:06:11.184
cells. And actually, this is comparisons between

107
00:06:11.544 --> 00:06:14.384
single-cell RNA-seq or single-nucleus RNA-seq and Slide-Tags, and you can see the

108
00:06:14.404 --> 00:06:18.004
cell type proportions, the number of molecules, which is in the thousands, and the

109
00:06:18.024 --> 00:06:21.684
counts are all the same. And most importantly,

110
00:06:23.304 --> 00:06:25.704
this technology has been commercialized by Tecan Tecara.

111
00:06:25.764 --> 00:06:29.394
I don't have any financial interest into Tecara, but they licensed the technology,

112
00:06:29.864 --> 00:06:33.844
and they've made it compatible with FFP through 10x Flex.

113
00:06:34.404 --> 00:06:38.304
And we've just been consistently very impressed by the

114
00:06:38.344 --> 00:06:39.144
data from

115
00:06:39.984 --> 00:06:43.524
this Flex in this spatial tagging of

116
00:06:43.644 --> 00:06:46.704
FFP samples. Here is a melanoma specimen.

117
00:06:47.054 --> 00:06:50.964
And on the exact same paired specimen, we ran it on Visium HD, and

118
00:06:51.004 --> 00:06:54.644
you can here see the median UMIs per cell, and genes per cell,

119
00:06:55.304 --> 00:06:57.844
for the single-cell technology versus,

120
00:06:58.904 --> 00:07:02.364
well, Flex versus Visium HD. And I think you can really

121
00:07:02.404 --> 00:07:06.264
appreciate that the true single-cell resolution in

122
00:07:06.324 --> 00:07:10.104
combination with molecular resolution gives you much, much better separation

123
00:07:10.144 --> 00:07:11.364
between cell types and states.

124
00:07:12.924 --> 00:07:14.344
That's all I'll say about the technology.

125
00:07:15.064 --> 00:07:18.494
We've been using this as a

126
00:07:18.524 --> 00:07:22.164
workhorse and it's readily available for you all.

127
00:07:23.604 --> 00:07:27.514
And so, I think a question that many of us, and you'll see in this

128
00:07:27.514 --> 00:07:31.424
series of talks we'll try to answer is, how are tumor cells

129
00:07:31.444 --> 00:07:34.134
and immune cells organized and shaped by their microenvironment?

130
00:07:34.644 --> 00:07:38.564
We're quite interested in how cell-intrinsic states are shaped by their

131
00:07:38.644 --> 00:07:42.084
neighborhood and the niche of the cells that they live in.

132
00:07:42.184 --> 00:07:46.134
And for example, tumor cells obviously have some dynamic evolution through the

133
00:07:46.164 --> 00:07:49.754
course of the tumor, whether that's genomic evolution through genetic and

134
00:07:49.844 --> 00:07:53.564
epigenetic means, as well as transcriptomic adaptations to their local

135
00:07:53.604 --> 00:07:57.524
environment. And that evolution is actually, through the course of the tumor,

136
00:07:57.584 --> 00:08:01.174
is in some equilibrium with the environment, right?

137
00:08:01.204 --> 00:08:04.684
It's driven in many part by the immune cells and stromal cells.

138
00:08:04.724 --> 00:08:05.124
And

139
00:08:06.044 --> 00:08:09.004
many of you guys here know this and are appreciative of this because it's very

140
00:08:09.024 --> 00:08:12.744
therapeutically relevant. Because many of our ways of modulating the immune

141
00:08:12.824 --> 00:08:16.604
system actually needs to take advantage of what our understanding of

142
00:08:16.844 --> 00:08:20.544
this equilibrium and evolution. Also targeted therapies as well.

143
00:08:21.604 --> 00:08:25.344
And so for example, response to checkpoint blockade in melanoma is

144
00:08:25.404 --> 00:08:28.024
highly bimodal, and it's really

145
00:08:29.104 --> 00:08:31.704
unclear what drives this bimodality.

146
00:08:31.764 --> 00:08:35.534
We speculate it is something to do with the immune microenvironment.

147
00:08:35.595 --> 00:08:39.424
There are many papers around it. But how do we actually understand

148
00:08:39.704 --> 00:08:43.044
if cell states within the cancer are associated with the

149
00:08:43.084 --> 00:08:46.824
microenvironment? And so we've been looking at spatial

150
00:08:46.884 --> 00:08:49.534
niches within the melanoma microenvironment,

151
00:08:50.484 --> 00:08:53.944
in particular in metastatic melanoma, using Slide-Tags.

152
00:08:53.964 --> 00:08:56.424
We actually did this in our original Slide-Tags paper.

153
00:08:56.464 --> 00:08:59.934
I'll show you one tissue as an example, and then I'll

154
00:08:59.944 --> 00:09:03.444
generalize these observations over many samples.

155
00:09:03.484 --> 00:09:04.434
So here is

156
00:09:05.604 --> 00:09:07.724
one of our first Slide Tag specimens on a melanoma.

157
00:09:08.144 --> 00:09:09.774
You can see there are these

158
00:09:11.284 --> 00:09:14.024
two histological regions of the tumor.

159
00:09:14.944 --> 00:09:18.364
And when you perform single-cell RNA-seq, here is the UMAP.

160
00:09:18.424 --> 00:09:21.564
You can see very fine-grained resolution of cell states, and then you can place the

161
00:09:21.604 --> 00:09:24.544
majority of these cells back into space here.

162
00:09:24.564 --> 00:09:28.304
And actually, if you just look at, this is tumor cells, you can see that they

163
00:09:28.324 --> 00:09:31.804
adopt a couple of transcriptionally distinct states that are also

164
00:09:31.924 --> 00:09:35.894
spatially distinct. And actually, these distinct transcriptional

165
00:09:35.984 --> 00:09:39.954
states, they turned out to actually also have kind of different CNVs

166
00:09:40.004 --> 00:09:43.894
that represent different evolutionary histories of these two clones, and they

167
00:09:43.894 --> 00:09:45.764
have very distinct cellular neighborhoods.

168
00:09:46.104 --> 00:09:49.584
Here's just a very, very simple analysis where blue represents

169
00:09:49.624 --> 00:09:50.124
the

170
00:09:51.404 --> 00:09:55.344
kind of depletion of cell types in the local microenvironment, while red represents

171
00:09:55.354 --> 00:09:59.264
the enrichment. And you can see generally, tumor cells in state one

172
00:09:59.304 --> 00:10:03.234
are relatively depleted in immune cells in their neighborhood, and

173
00:10:03.244 --> 00:10:07.174
then there's a particular enrichment in T cells in tumor cells with

174
00:10:07.244 --> 00:10:07.723
state two.

175
00:10:08.584 --> 00:10:12.544
And actually, you can go and use, here we used 10x Phi

176
00:10:12.664 --> 00:10:16.624
Prime to map the TCR sequences in single cell, but now

177
00:10:16.644 --> 00:10:19.364
we have the spatial localizations of those TCR sequences.

178
00:10:19.724 --> 00:10:23.594
And you can see here this particular T cell clone that's actually driving this

179
00:10:23.624 --> 00:10:26.983
enrichment to state two and depletion in state one.

180
00:10:27.663 --> 00:10:28.024
Here, the

181
00:10:28.864 --> 00:10:32.814
gray represents all T cells in this spatial context, and purple represents this

182
00:10:32.824 --> 00:10:34.304
particular clone.

183
00:10:35.464 --> 00:10:38.704
And you can, without any statistics, you can just see by eye that there's this

184
00:10:38.764 --> 00:10:42.704
strong tumor state and T cell clone association.

185
00:10:42.744 --> 00:10:46.684
So what's driving both this clone dependence and this T cell

186
00:10:47.064 --> 00:10:50.864
depletion? And we had a couple theories,

187
00:10:50.904 --> 00:10:54.324
one of which is that melanoma

188
00:10:54.334 --> 00:10:58.144
dedifferentiates during the course of progression, and

189
00:10:58.184 --> 00:11:01.944
as along to this more mesenchymal-like or neural crest-like

190
00:11:01.964 --> 00:11:05.584
phenotype. And along the way, then it can lose both its

191
00:11:05.684 --> 00:11:09.064
endogenous antigens or maybe it can drive a more immunosuppressive

192
00:11:09.104 --> 00:11:12.744
niche. And you can kind of already see that in the H&amp;E.

193
00:11:12.764 --> 00:11:15.404
And this is something that clinicians see all the time that

194
00:11:16.964 --> 00:11:20.784
melanomas are often pigmented before treatment, but during treatment

195
00:11:20.824 --> 00:11:24.304
they lose their pigment. But in this particular sample, you can see that the two

196
00:11:24.344 --> 00:11:27.884
lobes, histological lobes of this metastasis actually have

197
00:11:27.904 --> 00:11:31.444
differential pigmentation. And indeed, when you look

198
00:11:31.504 --> 00:11:35.244
at just the transcriptome scoring for these mesenchymal-like states,

199
00:11:35.444 --> 00:11:39.304
you see this difference where tumor one has adopted this more

200
00:11:39.384 --> 00:11:42.424
mesenchymal-like state and lost endogenous antigens.

201
00:11:43.484 --> 00:11:43.844
And so,

202
00:11:45.064 --> 00:11:46.804
this is just one sample. We've then

203
00:11:47.764 --> 00:11:51.344
have been systematically profiling many metastatic

204
00:11:51.924 --> 00:11:55.284
biopsies, 27 or approximately 30 so far actually

205
00:11:55.344 --> 00:11:56.384
now. And

206
00:11:57.684 --> 00:12:01.524
I'm skipping a lot of the analysis and data, and I just want to show you two

207
00:12:01.604 --> 00:12:04.714
highlights for what we see. One is that

208
00:12:05.184 --> 00:12:08.964
this dedifferentiation trajectory actually promote

209
00:12:09.004 --> 00:12:12.764
different niches correlated with the cancer cell state.

210
00:12:13.384 --> 00:12:17.234
Here you can see-On the rows of this heat

211
00:12:17.274 --> 00:12:20.714
map, different states of tumor cells, whether they're

212
00:12:20.734 --> 00:12:24.564
melanocytic or this neural crest transitory phenotype, and I

213
00:12:24.614 --> 00:12:26.354
haven't shown the fully undifferentiated here.

214
00:12:26.814 --> 00:12:30.794
But in particular, we observe that the neural crest transitory state is strongly

215
00:12:30.834 --> 00:12:34.454
associated with a particular immune suppressive

216
00:12:34.514 --> 00:12:38.434
neighborhood consisted of this SPP1 positive macrophage

217
00:12:38.454 --> 00:12:41.554
and this fibroblast that's post-N positive.

218
00:12:41.794 --> 00:12:42.244
So this is

219
00:12:43.934 --> 00:12:45.914
an immunosuppressive

220
00:12:47.094 --> 00:12:48.354
macrophage population, and then

221
00:12:49.814 --> 00:12:50.354
a

222
00:12:51.334 --> 00:12:53.274
tumor-associated fibroblast population.

223
00:12:53.614 --> 00:12:56.234
And association with this is exactly

224
00:12:56.254 --> 00:13:00.134
anti-correlated with many, basically effector

225
00:13:00.214 --> 00:13:03.754
CD8 T cells and also associated macrophage

226
00:13:03.814 --> 00:13:06.644
populations that we term an immune effector population.

227
00:13:07.034 --> 00:13:10.724
And when you're next to an immune effector population, we see that the cancer cells

228
00:13:10.754 --> 00:13:13.934
generally actually are interferon stimulated and dying.

229
00:13:13.974 --> 00:13:17.854
So, basically de-differentiation to this neural crest state

230
00:13:18.134 --> 00:13:21.134
causes this association with this

231
00:13:21.194 --> 00:13:23.494
immunosuppressive niche that also

232
00:13:24.874 --> 00:13:27.174
is anti-correlated with the effector status.

233
00:13:27.854 --> 00:13:31.164
And actually, not only is it anti-correlated with these cell types,

234
00:13:31.534 --> 00:13:34.994
the T cell clones are suppressed in the niche associated with

235
00:13:35.054 --> 00:13:38.864
SPP1 max and post-N fibroblasts. So, in

236
00:13:38.914 --> 00:13:42.384
those niches, if you look at T cell clonality, most T cells are

237
00:13:42.434 --> 00:13:43.394
singletons,

238
00:13:44.574 --> 00:13:48.374
or many more are singletons versus inside of this effector niche,

239
00:13:48.934 --> 00:13:52.254
many more are expanded, meaning they're dividing.

240
00:13:53.154 --> 00:13:55.674
Okay. And so what's going on with this?

241
00:13:56.414 --> 00:14:00.094
Well, we know SPP1 is one of these wound-associated

242
00:14:00.154 --> 00:14:03.634
macrophage factors, and it's probably a wound-healing

243
00:14:03.754 --> 00:14:06.994
program that also suppresses the local immune

244
00:14:07.034 --> 00:14:10.894
response. And we did some functional interrogation of...

245
00:14:11.594 --> 00:14:13.424
These are secreted factors, right?

