01:10:40.744 --> 01:10:42.724
others correspond to the microenvironment.

1225
01:10:43.424 --> 01:10:47.204
And we can assign each spot in the Visium to the main signal

1226
01:10:47.264 --> 01:10:51.204
that we see in that spot, and this is how two of those tumors look like.

1227
01:10:51.764 --> 01:10:55.464
But of course, there was still this challenge with the resolution of the spots.

1228
01:10:55.504 --> 01:10:59.324
So each spot contains approximately 10 cells, and we

1229
01:10:59.364 --> 01:11:02.864
wanted to better understand what is happening within those spots.

1230
01:11:03.484 --> 01:11:04.544
So to address this, we

1231
01:11:05.444 --> 01:11:08.954
went into the CODEX data to see what

1232
01:11:09.064 --> 01:11:12.824
happens within a given spot. And what we saw is that

1233
01:11:12.924 --> 01:11:16.684
even though a typical spot is indeed a combination of

1234
01:11:16.724 --> 01:11:19.964
multiple cell states or cell types, typically,

1235
01:11:20.584 --> 01:11:24.304
and more specifically in 64% of the spots, we see that

1236
01:11:24.504 --> 01:11:28.344
one cell state or one cell type controls the vast majority of

1237
01:11:28.384 --> 01:11:31.264
the cells in a given spot.

1238
01:11:32.264 --> 01:11:35.964
So the Visium data still gives us a good amount of

1239
01:11:36.004 --> 01:11:39.944
information about the main signal in a given spot, which is often

1240
01:11:39.984 --> 01:11:43.584
sufficient to really understand the organization of the tumor.

1241
01:11:44.704 --> 01:11:48.284
This also tells us a lot about the biology of glioma, that the cells are really

1242
01:11:48.344 --> 01:11:49.554
clustering together.

1243
01:11:50.524 --> 01:11:53.744
And we wanted to better understand to what degree the cells are clustering, not

1244
01:11:53.764 --> 01:11:57.484
just within one specific spot, but in larger areas than

1245
01:11:57.524 --> 01:11:57.824
that.

1246
01:11:58.764 --> 01:12:02.424
So we expanded from analyzing individual spots to looking at

1247
01:12:02.484 --> 01:12:06.424
adjacent spots, and we defined this measure of spatial coherence,

1248
01:12:06.984 --> 01:12:10.944
which is basically asking, after we assign each spot to the dominant

1249
01:12:11.024 --> 01:12:14.524
state, how many of the neighboring spot for one

1250
01:12:14.584 --> 01:12:18.524
specific spot are still dominated by the same state?

1251
01:12:19.804 --> 01:12:23.644
So we see variation in spatial coherence between different

1252
01:12:23.784 --> 01:12:27.704
cell states, for example, higher coherence for this mesenchymal hypoxia

1253
01:12:27.784 --> 01:12:31.744
state in yellow. We see variation between different regions of the

1254
01:12:31.804 --> 01:12:35.424
same sample, and we see a lot of variability between

1255
01:12:35.484 --> 01:12:39.364
different samples. And surprisingly, this was actually the strongest effect that we

1256
01:12:39.424 --> 01:12:39.724
saw.

1257
01:12:40.704 --> 01:12:44.384
So there were some samples in which overall, we saw high spatial

1258
01:12:44.424 --> 01:12:48.284
coherence. So almost wherever you look in this particular sample,

1259
01:12:48.844 --> 01:12:52.584
you see that spots are surrounded by other spots, often with the same

1260
01:12:52.684 --> 01:12:55.204
color. This is what we call a structured sample.

1261
01:12:56.184 --> 01:12:59.884
And in other samples, we see very limited spatial coherence.

1262
01:12:59.924 --> 01:13:03.740
This is what we call a disorganized sample.And

1263
01:13:03.860 --> 01:13:07.760
overall, we could divide the vast majority of the samples to either

1264
01:13:08.040 --> 01:13:11.860
mostly structural or mostly disorganized, and there were very

1265
01:13:12.000 --> 01:13:15.660
few cases that showed both of these behaviors within one

1266
01:13:15.720 --> 01:13:16.260
sample.

1267
01:13:17.640 --> 01:13:21.500
So we next wanted to better understand what is creating this dichotomy

1268
01:13:21.520 --> 01:13:23.500
of structured versus disorganized.

1269
01:13:23.960 --> 01:13:27.820
And the main difference that we saw between those samples was, again, the

1270
01:13:27.860 --> 01:13:30.460
presence of this mesenchymal hypoxia state.

1271
01:13:31.220 --> 01:13:34.200
And this suggests that whenever we have a high degree of

1272
01:13:34.480 --> 01:13:38.440
hypoxia, not only the immediate cells in that region

1273
01:13:38.500 --> 01:13:42.480
are affected and express this mesenchymal hypoxia state, but

1274
01:13:42.540 --> 01:13:46.260
also the entire tissue becomes more organized, suggesting that

1275
01:13:46.300 --> 01:13:50.080
hypoxia might have a long-range effect on the organization of the

1276
01:13:50.140 --> 01:13:53.930
tissue. So to better understand the organization that

1277
01:13:53.980 --> 01:13:57.740
emerges in these cases, we next asked what

1278
01:13:57.960 --> 01:14:01.760
was the colocalization between pairs of cell states or

1279
01:14:01.820 --> 01:14:02.460
cell types.

1280
01:14:03.460 --> 01:14:07.180
So in this graph, each node is a cell state or a

1281
01:14:07.240 --> 01:14:11.140
cell type, and the edges corresponds to a significant degree

1282
01:14:11.180 --> 01:14:14.060
of colocalization across all of the data sets.

1283
01:14:15.040 --> 01:14:15.800
And as you can see,

1284
01:14:16.720 --> 01:14:20.550
this analysis divides all the cell states and cell types into five different

1285
01:14:20.580 --> 01:14:24.480
groups or five different layers, such that all the edges are either

1286
01:14:24.540 --> 01:14:28.100
within a given layer or between adjacent layers.

1287
01:14:28.120 --> 01:14:32.100
And this, again, is consistent with the role of hypoxia in organizing

1288
01:14:32.140 --> 01:14:36.000
the tissue. So the first layer is where we see the actual mesenchymal

1289
01:14:36.040 --> 01:14:39.640
hypoxia spots and also the necrotic spots, the necrotic

1290
01:14:39.740 --> 01:14:40.200
regions.

1291
01:14:41.140 --> 01:14:44.940
The second layer corresponds to other mesenchymal states and inflammatory

1292
01:14:44.980 --> 01:14:48.700
macrophages that are adjacent to the hypoxic regions.

1293
01:14:49.440 --> 01:14:52.580
Then in the third layer, we see a lot of vascular cells,

1294
01:14:52.720 --> 01:14:56.480
macrophages that secrete VEGF, and so

1295
01:14:56.580 --> 01:15:00.060
this appears to be the layer that is trying to resolve the hypoxia.

1296
01:15:00.560 --> 01:15:04.400
And then in the fourth layer, we see many more of the cancer

1297
01:15:04.500 --> 01:15:07.840
cells in a neurodevelopmental state that is

1298
01:15:07.860 --> 01:15:10.240
presumably more dependent on oxygen.

1299
01:15:10.800 --> 01:15:14.140
Finally, in the fifth layer, the furthest away from the hypoxia,

1300
01:15:14.820 --> 01:15:18.740
we begin to see the infiltration of the tumor to the normal brain, where

1301
01:15:18.780 --> 01:15:22.580
there are many normal brain parenchymal cells, like oligodendrocytes,

1302
01:15:22.680 --> 01:15:26.580
astrocytes, and neurons. So this suggests a model

1303
01:15:26.640 --> 01:15:30.380
for the organization of GBM that consists of five different

1304
01:15:30.460 --> 01:15:34.000
layers. Of course, we are not suggesting that they are very clean

1305
01:15:34.020 --> 01:15:37.860
layer. It's more of a probabilistic shift in the abundance of

1306
01:15:37.920 --> 01:15:40.340
different cell types and cell states.

1307
01:15:40.360 --> 01:15:44.140
And here you see an example of this from the Codex data, where we

1308
01:15:44.160 --> 01:15:47.880
start in the left from a region that is highly hypoxic with

1309
01:15:47.920 --> 01:15:51.760
this mesenchymal hypoxia state. And then gradually, we see

1310
01:15:51.820 --> 01:15:55.560
more of the other mesenchymal state, macrophages,

1311
01:15:55.640 --> 01:15:59.090
vascular cells, and towards the end, we begin to see more of the

1312
01:15:59.180 --> 01:16:01.800
neurodevelopmental cell states and the normal cells.

1313
01:16:03.360 --> 01:16:07.230
So overall, what we see is that in GBM, there are many regions that

1314
01:16:07.260 --> 01:16:10.740
are quite disorganized, but as we get close to the hypoxic

1315
01:16:10.800 --> 01:16:14.620
regions, we begin to see more structure emerging, both

1316
01:16:14.700 --> 01:16:18.350
in terms of cells being surrounded by cells that are similar to them,

1317
01:16:18.880 --> 01:16:22.500
as well as this approximate structure of five different

1318
01:16:22.880 --> 01:16:23.340
layers.

1319
01:16:24.920 --> 01:16:28.660
So this work in GBM was already published, and after finishing this,

1320
01:16:29.100 --> 01:16:32.860
we began to look at the second major type of glioma,

1321
01:16:33.420 --> 01:16:37.400
which are IDH mutant glioma. And so we

1322
01:16:37.440 --> 01:16:39.850
profiled both by Codex and by Visium,

1323
01:16:40.660 --> 01:16:43.920
34 IDH mutant samples covering both

1324
01:16:44.040 --> 01:16:47.700
astrocytomas and oligodendrogliomas of different grades.

1325
01:16:48.660 --> 01:16:52.320
And when we analyze the degree of structure in those samples,

1326
01:16:52.880 --> 01:16:56.420
we see that there's overall less structure in the IDH mutant

1327
01:16:56.520 --> 01:17:00.340
cases than in the GBMs, and there is more structure

1328
01:17:00.440 --> 01:17:02.660
in the high-grade cases,

1329
01:17:03.740 --> 01:17:07.260
which are more similar to GBM compared to the mid-grade cases.

1330
01:17:07.700 --> 01:17:11.280
So this is still very consistent with the role of hypoxia, because

1331
01:17:11.440 --> 01:17:14.200
hypoxia occurs mostly in the high-grade cases.

1332
01:17:14.900 --> 01:17:18.640
And so far, this is quite consistent with what we saw in the GBM

1333
01:17:18.680 --> 01:17:22.380
work. But what then surprised us is that when we looked at

1334
01:17:22.600 --> 01:17:26.550
low-grade cases, we saw much more structure than

1335
01:17:26.580 --> 01:17:29.080
the mid-grade and even the high-grade cases.

1336
01:17:29.560 --> 01:17:33.440
And in the low-grade cases, there was almost no hypoxia and almost no

1337
01:17:33.480 --> 01:17:37.340
necrosis, suggesting that something else is driving the

1338
01:17:37.360 --> 01:17:39.080
organization of these samples.

1339
01:17:40.940 --> 01:17:44.660
So in high-grade IDH mutant glioma, as well as in GBM,

1340
01:17:45.200 --> 01:17:48.940
we see these approximate layers in which,

1341
01:17:49.120 --> 01:17:52.760
as you can see in the bottom, the tumor really consists of these small

1342
01:17:52.800 --> 01:17:56.420
patches that are dominated by specific cell

1343
01:17:56.500 --> 01:18:00.320
states or cell types. In mid-grade cases, we begin to lose

1344
01:18:00.340 --> 01:18:03.900
this organization. There is still some degree of organization, but much

1345
01:18:03.940 --> 01:18:04.340
lower.

1346
01:18:05.200 --> 01:18:09.080
And then in the low-grade cases, again, we see more structure, but it's not

1347
01:18:09.260 --> 01:18:12.120
the same structure. We don't see again those patches.

1348
01:18:12.900 --> 01:18:16.780
Rather, we see pairs of cell states that are correlated in

1349
01:18:16.860 --> 01:18:20.420
their localization. So there's a different type of structure,

1350
01:18:20.960 --> 01:18:24.280
and we are trying to understand what is driving this structure, which

1351
01:18:24.920 --> 01:18:28.760
it probably not hypoxia. And what we are starting to

1352
01:18:28.820 --> 01:18:32.530
see is that in those low-grade cases, the normal

1353
01:18:32.680 --> 01:18:36.420
structures of the brain are still maintained to a large degree.

1354
01:18:36.500 --> 01:18:40.340
These normal structures have been eroded in the high-grade

1355
01:18:40.600 --> 01:18:44.320
cases, but in low-grade, they are still there, and they appear to

1356
01:18:44.720 --> 01:18:47.080
influence the organization of the tumor.

1357
01:18:47.620 --> 01:18:49.290
And I'm going to show you one example of this,

1358
01:18:50.320 --> 01:18:54.260
which is the division of the tumor to white matter, gray matter,

1359
01:18:54.520 --> 01:18:58.080
and the junction between them. So the normal brain is divided

1360
01:18:58.120 --> 01:19:01.100
into white and gray matter, as well as other regions.

1361
01:19:02.500 --> 01:19:06.240
And in the tumor, we can still see that division

1362
01:19:06.320 --> 01:19:08.630
quite nicely in the case of low-grade

1363
01:19:08.760 --> 01:19:12.752
tumors.Not only do we see white and gray matter, we also

1364
01:19:12.832 --> 01:19:16.472
see a very sharp junction that separates them.

1365
01:19:16.502 --> 01:19:19.652
And the fact that this is such a clean and sharp

1366
01:19:20.512 --> 01:19:24.452
structure suggests that this has been maintained despite the

1367
01:19:24.492 --> 01:19:25.472
growth of the tumor.

1368
01:19:26.412 --> 01:19:29.992
So next, we wanted to see how this influences the

1369
01:19:30.052 --> 01:19:33.642
cells around that junction. So we counted the number of cells

1370
01:19:34.852 --> 01:19:38.432
moving from the white matter through the junction and to

1371
01:19:38.472 --> 01:19:42.312
the gray matter, and we saw that this actually serves as a

1372
01:19:42.371 --> 01:19:44.192
barrier for the growth of the tumor.

1373
01:19:44.652 --> 01:19:48.552
So the density of cells drops dramatically as we

1374
01:19:48.612 --> 01:19:50.752
switch from the white matter to the gray matter.

1375
01:19:51.382 --> 01:19:55.212
And this was surprising for us to see because in the context of glioma, we

1376
01:19:55.272 --> 01:19:59.032
normally think about tumors that diffuse in the brain and that

1377
01:19:59.072 --> 01:20:01.352
expand almost with no interruption.

1378
01:20:01.832 --> 01:20:05.472
And here we see that this junction between white and gray matter is

1379
01:20:05.532 --> 01:20:08.451
in fact a barrier for the growth of the tumor.

1380
01:20:09.832 --> 01:20:13.432
So not only the overall density of cells dropped at this

1381
01:20:13.492 --> 01:20:17.012
junction, but also the fraction of cells that are

1382
01:20:17.052 --> 01:20:20.892
malignant further dropped, suggesting that this is

1383
01:20:20.932 --> 01:20:22.831
really stopping the growth of the tumor.

1384
01:20:23.352 --> 01:20:26.012
At the same time, there are changes in the microenvironment.

1385
01:20:26.272 --> 01:20:29.332
We see, of course, many more neurons in the gray matter,

1386
01:20:30.012 --> 01:20:34.002
and we see almost no macrophages as we pass from

1387
01:20:34.032 --> 01:20:36.032
the white matter to the gray matter.

1388
01:20:37.352 --> 01:20:41.272
We can go deeper into this and ask not just about the overall

1389
01:20:41.312 --> 01:20:44.812
amount of malignant cells, but about the specific states of the

1390
01:20:44.852 --> 01:20:48.592
malignant cells. And we see that as we go through the junction,

1391
01:20:49.132 --> 01:20:52.792
we see an enrichment of OPC-like cells, a

1392
01:20:53.392 --> 01:20:56.232
further depletion of astrocyte-like cells.

1393
01:20:56.712 --> 01:21:00.432
And just around the junction, we see some enrichment of

1394
01:21:00.572 --> 01:21:01.992
undifferentiated cells.

1395
01:21:02.852 --> 01:21:06.712
And even for the state that is enriched after the junction, the

1396
01:21:06.772 --> 01:21:10.292
OPC-like cells, we can go deeper into this and look at specific

1397
01:21:10.392 --> 01:21:13.952
markers, and we see that almost all of them are changing

1398
01:21:14.032 --> 01:21:17.612
significantly. So even for a given cell state,

1399
01:21:18.072 --> 01:21:21.652
we see more subtle changes in the degree of differentiation

1400
01:21:22.132 --> 01:21:25.052
as cells move from the white matter to the gray matter.

1401
01:21:26.512 --> 01:21:30.032
And so to summarize the analysis in glioma, we see two different

1402
01:21:30.072 --> 01:21:33.692
behaviors. We see in high-grade cases, as well as in GBM,

1403
01:21:34.112 --> 01:21:37.352
that hypoxia and necrosis appear to organize the tumor.

1404
01:21:37.932 --> 01:21:41.672
But in low-grade cases where there is almost no hypoxia and necrosis,

1405
01:21:42.212 --> 01:21:45.772
it seems like residual brain parenchymal structures are

1406
01:21:45.852 --> 01:21:49.532
organizing the tumor. And specifically, this junction

1407
01:21:49.572 --> 01:21:52.452
between the white and gray matter serves

1408
01:21:53.692 --> 01:21:56.092
as a barrier for the growth of the tumor.

1409
01:21:56.152 --> 01:21:59.792
And around this barrier we see significant changes in the

1410
01:21:59.812 --> 01:22:03.392
composition of cell types and cell states, and specifically the

1411
01:22:03.452 --> 01:22:07.372
OPC-like cells are the ones that appear to be most capable

1412
01:22:07.412 --> 01:22:08.412
of migrating

1413
01:22:09.292 --> 01:22:13.042
along this border, which is very consistent with the ability of

1414
01:22:13.092 --> 01:22:16.492
OPC-like cells to migrate during development.

1415
01:22:19.712 --> 01:22:23.472
So now I want to switch from glioma to head and neck cancer.

1416
01:22:23.792 --> 01:22:27.712
So also in head and neck cancer, we see specific cell states that are

1417
01:22:27.772 --> 01:22:29.672
commonly observed in many tumors.

1418
01:22:29.732 --> 01:22:32.232
Here I'm showing just one tumor as an example.

1419
01:22:33.132 --> 01:22:36.512
These main cell states include cell cycle related states,

1420
01:22:36.832 --> 01:22:40.192
stress states, states reflecting epithelial

1421
01:22:40.252 --> 01:22:41.752
differentiation and senescence.

1422
01:22:42.132 --> 01:22:45.692
And one state that I'm going to come back to because it's particularly

1423
01:22:45.712 --> 01:22:49.692
important clinically is a state that resembles epithelial

1424
01:22:49.732 --> 01:22:53.032
to mesenchymal transition with dementin,

1425
01:22:53.112 --> 01:22:56.332
podoplanin, TGF-beta responsive genes, and others.

1426
01:22:56.872 --> 01:22:59.332
Now, this is a very partial form of EMT.

1427
01:22:59.412 --> 01:23:02.912
The cells do not lose expression of epithelial markers.

1428
01:23:03.012 --> 01:23:06.792
They also do not gain expression of canonical EMT

1429
01:23:06.872 --> 01:23:09.752
factors like SNAI, ZEB, and Twist.

1430
01:23:10.932 --> 01:23:13.832
But this partial EMT is still

1431
01:23:13.892 --> 01:23:17.632
associated with metastasis as well as

1432
01:23:17.712 --> 01:23:19.772
with poor overall survival.

1433
01:23:21.772 --> 01:23:25.332
So we applied Visium as well as Codex to

1434
01:23:25.532 --> 01:23:28.752
28 head and neck cancer samples covering different

1435
01:23:29.812 --> 01:23:31.692
sites and different genetic classes.

1436
01:23:32.372 --> 01:23:35.672
And again, with the Visium data, we are able to

1437
01:23:35.712 --> 01:23:39.512
identify all of the main patterns that we expect to see in those

1438
01:23:39.592 --> 01:23:42.452
tumors directly from the Visium data.

1439
01:23:42.492 --> 01:23:46.352
We divide the spots into the malignant spots, those where we see

1440
01:23:46.432 --> 01:23:50.312
a strong signal for chromosomal aberrations, and to the

1441
01:23:50.352 --> 01:23:52.692
non-malignant spots where we don't see this signal.

1442
01:23:53.732 --> 01:23:57.392
And again, overall, we see high consistency between the single-cell

1443
01:23:57.472 --> 01:24:01.432
data and the spatial data. But there was one interesting exception,

1444
01:24:01.992 --> 01:24:05.492
which is that in the malignant spots, we see a

1445
01:24:05.532 --> 01:24:09.292
program that we call the inflammatory response that

1446
01:24:09.312 --> 01:24:13.132
consists primarily of genes that are often

1447
01:24:13.172 --> 01:24:17.152
cytokines and chemokines that we know from the single-cell data are

1448
01:24:17.192 --> 01:24:20.772
expressed not by the cancer cells, but actually by myeloid cells,

1449
01:24:20.992 --> 01:24:23.132
either macrophages or neutrophils.

1450
01:24:24.682 --> 01:24:28.532
So this indicates, and we can validate this with the Codex data,

1451
01:24:28.572 --> 01:24:32.472
that there is a strong colocalization of cancer cells with

1452
01:24:32.572 --> 01:24:36.541
myeloid cells that are active and produce many cytokines and

1453
01:24:36.612 --> 01:24:37.272
chemokines.

1454
01:24:38.452 --> 01:24:41.232
And I will get back to this program later on.

1455
01:24:42.232 --> 01:24:46.162
So next, we wanted to better understand the organization of head and

1456
01:24:46.162 --> 01:24:49.832
neck tumors. So again, we asked about the colocalization of these

1457
01:24:49.872 --> 01:24:52.232
different cell states and cell types.

1458
01:24:52.312 --> 01:24:56.252
And what we saw, unlike glioma, is a global division into

1459
01:24:56.352 --> 01:25:00.132
immune-rich compartments, stromal-rich compartment, and cancer-rich compartment.

1460
01:25:00.212 --> 01:25:04.052
Again, with this exception of inflammatory response of myeloid

1461
01:25:04.112 --> 01:25:07.892
cells embedded in the region that is mostly cancer-rich.

1462
01:25:09.232 --> 01:25:12.952
And next, we wanted to better understand the organization within the cancer

1463
01:25:13.032 --> 01:25:16.812
compartment. So we defined another analysis that we called

1464
01:25:17.192 --> 01:25:20.888
a zonation analysis.In this case, every spot

1465
01:25:21.028 --> 01:25:25.008
that is dominated by immuno stromal cells is considered

1466
01:25:25.408 --> 01:25:29.328
in the non-epithelial zone. After that, all the spots that

1467
01:25:29.348 --> 01:25:32.928
are dominated by cancer cells but are bordering the

1468
01:25:32.968 --> 01:25:36.148
non-epithelial zone are considered as the tumor edge.

1469
01:25:36.908 --> 01:25:40.768
The spots that are dominated by cancer cells and that then border

1470
01:25:40.988 --> 01:25:44.948
the tumor edge are the mid-tumor. And finally, the spots

1471
01:25:45.008 --> 01:25:48.808
dominated by cancer cells that are only bordering the mid-tumor are

1472
01:25:48.868 --> 01:25:52.108
called the core of the tumor. And so basically, we are

1473
01:25:52.128 --> 01:25:55.988
dividing all the spots based on how far away they are

1474
01:25:56.228 --> 01:26:00.088
from the stromal regions. And here you see an example

1475
01:26:00.128 --> 01:26:02.388
of how it applies to one specific tumor.

1476
01:26:04.108 --> 01:26:08.088
So we apply this to all of the tumors, and then we can ask for every cell state,

1477
01:26:08.168 --> 01:26:10.958
how is it distributed across these different zones.

1478
01:26:11.288 --> 01:26:15.188
And I'm going to focus on the analysis of this partial EMT that I

1479
01:26:15.248 --> 01:26:18.988
highlighted a few slides ago.

1480
01:26:19.168 --> 01:26:22.828
So here you see in black the overall pattern of partial

1481
01:26:22.908 --> 01:26:26.448
EMT across all samples, and the thinner lines in the background

1482
01:26:26.528 --> 01:26:28.608
correspond to individual tumors.

1483
01:26:28.748 --> 01:26:32.328
So you can see that the average pattern doesn't really reflect what's happening

1484
01:26:32.748 --> 01:26:36.388
in individual tumors. And the individual tumors can actually

1485
01:26:36.468 --> 01:26:39.228
be separated into two main patterns.

1486
01:26:39.468 --> 01:26:43.448
In some samples, we see EMT enriched at the edge of the tumor,

1487
01:26:43.668 --> 01:26:46.648
and this is consistent with a lot of literature about EMT.

1488
01:26:47.128 --> 01:26:51.088
But then in other samples, we see EMT mostly enriched

1489
01:26:51.108 --> 01:26:55.028
at the core of the tumor. And we could validate this by staining for

1490
01:26:55.068 --> 01:26:58.668
LAMC2, which is a top marker for this partial EMT

1491
01:26:58.678 --> 01:27:02.128
program. And importantly, when we analyze multiple

1492
01:27:02.608 --> 01:27:06.328
samples of the same tumor, we see that this result is

1493
01:27:06.368 --> 01:27:10.268
highly consistent. If a tumor has EMT at the edge in one sample,

1494
01:27:10.348 --> 01:27:14.068
it's usually going to have the same pattern in other samples of the same

1495
01:27:14.108 --> 01:27:14.428
tumor.

1496
01:27:15.928 --> 01:27:17.848
So this suggests that we are seeing two different

1497
01:27:18.768 --> 01:27:22.728
subtypes of tumors. And so we asked what else is different between them.

1498
01:27:23.218 --> 01:27:26.548
And some of the main differences that we saw include more

1499
01:27:26.588 --> 01:27:30.548
lymphocytes in tumors with EMT at the edge and

1500
01:27:30.608 --> 01:27:34.328
more of this inflammatory response, more of these myeloid

1501
01:27:34.368 --> 01:27:38.288
cells in tumors where EMT is at the core of the tumor.

1502
01:27:38.808 --> 01:27:42.768
And this suggests that perhaps this inflammatory response might be

1503
01:27:42.788 --> 01:27:45.948
inducing partial EMT at the core of the tumor.

1504
01:27:46.528 --> 01:27:47.648
So to ask this, we

1505
01:27:48.948 --> 01:27:52.668
went back to this colocalization analysis, but now we

1506
01:27:52.768 --> 01:27:55.748
cleaned each of the edges based on whether this

1507
01:27:56.008 --> 01:27:59.828
colocalization is seen in all samples or whether it's seen

1508
01:27:59.908 --> 01:28:03.108
only in cases where EMT is at the core or at the edge.

1509
01:28:03.768 --> 01:28:07.198
And what we see is that partial EMT actually has two opposing

1510
01:28:07.268 --> 01:28:10.968
interactions. When the EMT is located at the edge of the

1511
01:28:10.988 --> 01:28:14.948
tumor, it's colocalized with the fibroblast, as you see with the

1512
01:28:15.008 --> 01:28:18.988
yellow edge. And when partial EMT is located at the core of

1513
01:28:19.028 --> 01:28:22.788
the tumor, it's instead colocalized with this inflammatory

1514
01:28:22.828 --> 01:28:26.808
response. And this suggests that there might be two different mechanisms

1515
01:28:26.908 --> 01:28:30.768
for microenvironment-based induction of partial

1516
01:28:30.788 --> 01:28:34.408
EMT. And we search for potential ligand receptor

1517
01:28:34.468 --> 01:28:36.228
interaction that might explain this.

1518
01:28:37.288 --> 01:28:41.068
The top prediction from the fibroblast was TGF-beta, which is, of

1519
01:28:41.148 --> 01:28:44.108
course, a well-known inducer of partial EMT.

1520
01:28:44.908 --> 01:28:48.498
And for the inflammatory response, the top prediction was oncostatin M.

1521
01:28:50.088 --> 01:28:53.928
So next, we treated two different head and neck cancer cell lines with

1522
01:28:53.968 --> 01:28:57.748
both oncostatin M and TGF-beta. And we saw that

1523
01:28:57.808 --> 01:29:01.788
both of these cytokines indeed are able to induce many

1524
01:29:01.828 --> 01:29:03.328
of the partial EMT genes.

1525
01:29:04.208 --> 01:29:07.988
Now, TGF-beta was more effectively inducing partial EMT in

1526
01:29:08.108 --> 01:29:11.848
this in vitro analysis. But in vivo,

1527
01:29:12.008 --> 01:29:15.988
we see the same partial EMT program when it's at the core and

1528
01:29:16.008 --> 01:29:19.908
at the edge, suggesting that perhaps there are other mechanism and that

1529
01:29:19.948 --> 01:29:23.108
there is convergence to the same partial EMT program.

1530
01:29:25.408 --> 01:29:28.828
So to summarize, we see in head and neck cancer a global division to

1531
01:29:28.868 --> 01:29:32.828
immune-rich, stroma-rich, and cancer-rich compartment with this exception

1532
01:29:32.908 --> 01:29:35.908
of myeloid cells in the cancer-rich compartment.

1533
01:29:37.308 --> 01:29:39.488
We see two main patterns of partial EMT.

1534
01:29:39.968 --> 01:29:43.448
At the edge, it seems to be induced by fibroblasts, and at the core of the

1535
01:29:43.488 --> 01:29:47.017
tumor, we believe that this might be induced by the myeloid cells and

1536
01:29:47.128 --> 01:29:50.728
specifically by oncostatin M. And in those

1537
01:29:50.788 --> 01:29:54.528
cases, we see an even lower amount of T cells and B

1538
01:29:54.608 --> 01:29:58.548
cells, suggesting that perhaps EMT at the core of the tumor might

1539
01:29:58.608 --> 01:30:01.468
have a stronger effect of immunosuppression.

1540
01:30:02.988 --> 01:30:06.768
So right now we are trying to better understand what determines the separation

1541
01:30:06.828 --> 01:30:10.668
into patients with EMT at the edge and those with EMT at the core,

1542
01:30:11.228 --> 01:30:13.728
and whether that would have any clinical implications.

1543
01:30:13.788 --> 01:30:14.528
For example,

1544
01:30:15.328 --> 01:30:18.818
it's easy to imagine that EMT at the core might have a stronger

1545
01:30:18.968 --> 01:30:22.608
immunosuppressive effect, going back to what I mentioned about

1546
01:30:22.748 --> 01:30:25.718
lower amount of lymphocytes. And perhaps EMT at the

1547
01:30:26.088 --> 01:30:30.058
edge might be more clearly linked to invasion and

1548
01:30:30.088 --> 01:30:33.808
metastasis. So this is some of the questions that we are trying to answer now.

1549
01:30:35.968 --> 01:30:39.048
So finally, I want to thank everyone that contributed to this work.

1550
01:30:39.608 --> 01:30:43.258
In my lab, the glioma work was led by Alisa, Reuven, and

1551
01:30:43.308 --> 01:30:47.188
Noam, and this was a great collaboration with Mario

1552
01:30:47.268 --> 01:30:49.568
Suva's lab and specifically with Chris Mount.

1553
01:30:50.448 --> 01:30:50.728
And

1554
01:30:51.588 --> 01:30:55.328
the work on head and neck cancer was led by Dor Simkin in my lab,

1555
01:30:55.768 --> 01:30:59.268
together with Sid Pouram's lab and specifically with Tom

1556
01:30:59.328 --> 01:31:01.788
Barrett. And thank you again for listening.

1557
01:31:07.948 --> 01:31:09.168
All right. Thank you.

1558
01:31:11.368 --> 01:31:14.508
Well, I guess you can email your questions to Yitai,

1559
01:31:15.428 --> 01:31:17.748
and thank you for joining this session.
